<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  A <strong>future</strong> reactive <code>consume()</code> handle — one that exposes the <em>current</em>
  provided value <em>and</em> lets a consumer wait for / iterate <em>future</em> <code>provide()</code> calls —
  must pick a shape <strong>before it is built</strong>. The prior survey
  (<code>reports/2026-06-26-consumable-await-footgun.md</code>) found a footgun in the obvious shape: if the
  handle is a <strong>thenable</strong> (has a <code>get then()</code>), then <code>await consumable</code>
  <em>after</em> <code>consume()</code> already called <code>provide()</code> internally
  <strong>hangs forever</strong> — <code>await</code> waits for the <em>next</em> provide, which may never
  come. Worse, you cannot even <code>return</code> a thenable handle from an <code>async consume()</code>:
  the Promise Resolution Procedure unwraps it and the returned promise <em>follows</em> its (pending) state.
  So the question is the handle's shape: <strong>eliminate the thenable, keep the sync handle, or wrap it?</strong>
</p>

<h2>Finding 1 — the footgun is a FUTURE design call, not a buildable bug today</h2>
<p>
  Traced both repos. <code>webinjectors</code> <code>Injector.consume()</code> is <strong>already async and
  returns the provider value directly</strong> — <code>async consume(): Promise&lt;ProviderTypeMap[Key]&gt;</code>
  (<code>fui:plugs/webinjectors/Injector.ts:197</code>) — so <code>await injector.consume(...)</code> works and
  there is no thenable to hang on. <code>webcontexts</code> <code>CustomContext</code> exposes
  <code>get/set value</code> + <strong>callback subscriptions</strong>
  (<code>fui:plugs/webcontexts/CustomContext.ts:99-129</code>), not <code>await</code>/<code>for await</code>.
  The <code>get then()</code> thenable <code>Consumable</code> the report describes has <strong>zero
  occurrences in non-test source</strong> in either repo. The only in-tree <code>Consumable</code> is the
  <em>subscribe-based</em>, Apollo-Link interface (<code>we:resources/contract.ts:39</code> →
  <code>subscribe(observer)</code>, <strong>not</strong> a thenable). So the footgun is real <em>only</em> for
  a reactive-consume handle that does not yet exist — resolving it means picking that handle's shape ahead of
  the build.
</p>

<h2>Finding 2 — every reactive prior-art handle is value-via-property + stream-via-iterator, never await-for-value</h2>
<p>
  The <a href="https://github.com/tc39/proposal-signals">TC39 Signals proposal</a> reads a value with
  <code>.get()</code> (a synchronous pull, <strong>not</strong> a thenable); reactivity is an effect /
  <code>Signal.subtle.Watcher</code> primitive layered on top, never an <code>await</code>. Async iterators
  are the platform-native streaming primitive — <code>Symbol.asyncIterator</code> + <code>for await…of</code>,
  driven by <code>next()</code>, <strong>not</strong> <code>then</code>. RxJS <code>BehaviorSubject</code>
  exposes the latest value as <code>.value</code> (a property) and the stream via <code>.subscribe()</code>.
  Preact / Solid signals read via <code>.value</code> / a getter. Web <code>EventTarget</code> /
  <code>AbortSignal</code> read state synchronously (<code>signal.aborted</code>) and stream via events. The
  convergent shape across all of them: <strong>current value is a property/pull, future values are an
  iterator/effect/subscription</strong> — and <strong>none</strong> of them is await-able-for-the-current-value.
  A thenable reactive handle is the odd one out, and it is exactly the
  <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/async_function">thenable
  footgun class</a> MDN warns about: an async return value that is a thenable causes the returned promise to
  <em>follow</em> it, hanging forever if its <code>then</code> never settles.
</p>

<h2>Finding 3 — fork-existence: a thenable handle and a non-thenable handle cannot coexist</h2>
<p>
  The two branches are <strong>mutually-exclusive shapes for the same return value</strong>: the handle either
  has a <code>get then()</code> or it does not — a single object cannot be both at once, and the presence of
  <code>then</code> is precisely what makes <code>await consumable</code> hang. This is a genuine fork (case a:
  one branch is broken). The composability probe fails on purpose: you cannot build the thenable spelling as a
  facade over a non-thenable kernel without re-introducing the <code>then</code> that hangs. Because there is
  <strong>no live consumer</strong> of the thenable handle (it is unbuilt), there is nothing to migrate — the
  choice is free of back-compat.
</p>

<h2>Recommendation</h2>
<p>
  <strong>(a) Eliminate the thenable.</strong> The handle is not thenable: current value is
  <code>consumable.value</code>; waiting for the next provide is the <em>explicit</em>
  <code>await consumable.next()</code>; <code>for await…of</code> keeps working via
  <code>Symbol.asyncIterator</code>. The hang becomes <strong>impossible by construction</strong> (you cannot
  accidentally <code>await</code> a non-thenable into a pending state), which is the project's
  footgun-elimination-by-construction stance, and it aligns the handle with the value-pull + async-iterator
  prior art (native-first). Rejected: <strong>(b) keep sync + document</strong> — leaves the footgun and only
  warns in prose, violating eliminate-by-construction; <strong>(c) wrapper <code>{ consumable, value }</code></strong>
  — adds a clunky destructure and a second concept at every call site with no offsetting merit over (a).
</p>

